{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":3,"author":{"id":"4277d85693ce7ae3559eb0a94f3b50be93446600"},"timestamp":1332779764,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQ2OTgwNTc=","github-url":"https://github.com/parrot/parrot/issues/749#issuecomment-4698057"},"message":"At least with gcc, the decision of whether a header is treated as a system header is independant of the choice of quotes used in the inclusion.\n\nThe difference between `\"...\"` and `\u003c...\u003e` is just that the former first checks paths relative to the current input file, whereas the latter does not (see [this gist](https://gist.github.com/2204236) for a more complete story).\n\nIf a consistent differentiation between the two include directives is desired, two choices come to mind:\n- use `\"...\"` for relative paths and `\u003c...\u003e` otherwise\n- use `\"...\"` for project-internal headers and `\u003c...\u003e` for 3rd party headers\n\nThe 2nd choice has no technical benefit if `-iquote` is not used, but nevertheless could serve as documentation (though one might argue that the fact that internal headers use a path starting with `parrot/` should be documentation enough...)","files":null}]}